\series bold 
Objective
\series default 
 
\layout Standard

To understand the relationship between the direction of the force applied
 to an object and the direction of the acceleration of the object.
 
\layout Standard


\series bold 
Overview
\series default 
 
\layout Standard

In the previous lab you examined the one-dimensional motions of an object
 caused by a single force applied to the object.
 You have seen that when friction is so small that it can be ignored, a
 single constant applied force will cause an object to have a constant accelerat
ion.
 (The object will speed up at a steady rate.) 
\layout Standard

Under these conditions, you have seen that the acceleration is proportional
 to the applied force, if the mass of the object is not changed.
 You saw that when a constant force is applied to a cart, the cart speeds
 up at a constant rate so that it has a constant acceleration.
 If the applied force is made larger, then the acceleration is proportionally
 larger.
 This allows you to define force more precisely not just in terms of the
 stretches of rubber bands and springs, but as the entity (the "thing")
 that causes acceleration.
\layout Standard

The goal of this lab is to continue to develop the relationship between
 force and acceleration, an important part of the first two of Newton's
 famous laws of motion.
 You will explore motions in which the applied force (and hence the acceleration
 of the object) is in a different direction than the object's velocity.
 In this case the object is slowing down in the sense that its speed is
 decreasing.
\layout Standard


